Photo by @CristinaMittermeier // What makes you happy? Perhaps the feelings we attach to our cultural identity, the sense of belonging to a “tribe”, the pride in our language and traditions, the closeness to our friends and family?  Perhaps those feelings contribute in a much enduring way to our happiness than all the money in the world?  That awesome feeling of being enough, having enough, and doing enough is called Enoughness and as we enter a new year, I wish for that kind of happiness for all.  May you be Enough, do Enough, and have Enough in 2018!

A group of performers relaxes during a break from the annual Sing-Sing or cultural festival of the highlands of Papua New Guinea.

items.title: Rick Rubin // "Everyone has their own way of coping and dealing with the world... If something is painful, if you're sensitive or uncomfortable, if you feel like you're different, your choices are to examine this and figure it out, or to numb yourself and ignore it. Most people tend to numb themselves and ignore their problems to avoid how they feel. Most people...just look for ways to kill the pain. We live in a kill-the-pain society. TV kills the pain. Doctors prescribe drugs to kill the pain. Somehow I got into tuning into how I feel and trying to understand it."

items.title: From the archive. Blah Blah Blah Magazine Envelope. Commissioned by @marvinjarrett. Printed in early 1996 by our great friend - Steve at Pega Print in Sheffield, UK. Neil did the lions share of the design on this one - and I shared the design story behind the letterhead which accompanied this envelope last month. Envelopes then...back in the day when folks wrote letters, sent invoices, cheques, fan mail...licked stamps, scrawled an address down copied from an address book or Filofax and sent it via Her Majesty’s Royal Mail. Which reminded me of the wonderful experience of receiving letters and packages from complete strangers - illustrators, photographers, designers, writers, painters, typographers sharing their work and often these interactions turned into commissions - shoots or illustrations for either Blah Blah Blah or Ray Gun magazine. This was how I discovered Frank Maddocks who went on to create the screenprint for the Ray Gun 58 Andy Warhol Cover. Such a fantastically inspirational and non bureaucratic process. #swissgrit #blahblahblahmagazine #graphicdesign #design #type #typography #mtv #typedaily #dailytype #typographyinspiration #art #typeinspire #typeinspired  #deconstructedtype #graphics #sans #stationerydesign #logo #logodesign #masthead #brand #branding #designinspiration #din

items.title: From the archive. Ray Gun 46, Supergrass Feature: Opening Double Page Spread. Published in April '97. Gaz Coombes photographed by Julie Sleaford. The article coincided with the release of their second album titled 'In It For The Money', which was one that got continuous plays from me in the Ray Gun office throughout '97. A fantastic record. The interview for this article took place in a pub called 'The Slaughtered Pig' in their hometown of Oxford, England - and the title that I got from the writer (Ken Micallef) was 'Private Life' which spoke to the public spotlight aspect of being in a band - which they all detested. Julie's image was incredible, a designers dream in my opinion and I really enjoyed the challenge of combining typography with it. The crisp and clean nature of the photograph pushed me to create some simple, sharp typography - so I set all the elements on screen, printed them out, and scanned them back in so that they were malleable. I then did a simple typographic-play on the 'Private Life' title of the feature - by reversing and flipping most of it to create some abstraction and distance from the viewer, as well as trying to create some interaction between Gaz's lean and the headline type. I then added a little uneasiness by step-and-repeating a few of the characters. I pretty much spent my 18 months on Ray Gun listening to this album, 'Ultra', 'This Is Hardcore', 'Blur', Urban Hymns' and New Order's catalogue. items.title:
@timolenzen writes: This is a poster titled: No water no fun. So funny how flagrant another designer who sent in his work for your review copied & pasted the pool out of my artwork. ⠀
⠀
my review: First, your poster is wonderful. It communicates the issue without any words, always a challenge that you mastered beautifully. Second, about copying other people's work: Apart for the obvious moral issue, when a designer takes work from someone else, that person is depriving him/herself of one of the most lovely experiences one can have as a designer: To be the parent of a piece of work. Even if nobody ever detects that its borrowed from someone else, the borrower will always know. And so that person will never become the parent, always remain the babysitter. And as the babysitter one will never be able to care for the baby, to nurture and push it, as well as a parent could. ⠀
⠀
